# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: sms-gateways
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The **Global System for Mobile Communications** (**GSM**) is a family of standards to describe the protocols for second-generation (2G) digital cellular networks, as used by mobile devices such as mobile phones and mobile broadband modems.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM is also a trademark owned by the GSM Association.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] "GSM" may also refer to the voice codec initially used in GSM.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] 2G networks were developed as a replacement for first generation (1G) analog cellular networks.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The original GSM standard, which was developed by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI), originally described a digital, circuit-switched network optimized for full duplex voice telephony, employing time division multiple access (TDMA) between stations.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] This expanded over time to include data communications, first by circuit-switched transport, then by packet data transport via its upgraded standards, GPRS and then EDGE.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM exists in various versions based on the frequency bands used.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM was first implemented in Finland in December 1991.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] It became the global standard for mobile cellular communications, with over 2 billion GSM subscribers globally in 2006, far above its competing standard, CDMA.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Its share reached over 90% market share by the mid-2010s, and operating in over 219 countries and territories.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The specifications and maintenance of GSM passed over to the 3GPP body in 2000, which at the time developed third-generation (3G) UMTS standards, followed by the fourth-generation (4G) LTE Advanced and the fifth-generation 5G standards, which do not form part of the GSM standard.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Beginning in the late 2010s, various carriers worldwide started to shut down their GSM networks; nevertheless, as a result of the network's widespread use, the acronym "GSM" is still used as a generic term for the plethora of *G* mobile phone technologies evolved from it or mobile phones itself.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Five years later, in 1987, 15 representatives from 13 European countries signed a memorandum of understanding in Copenhagen to develop and deploy a common cellular telephone system across Europe, and EU rules were passed to make GSM a mandatory standard.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The decision to develop a continental standard eventually resulted in a unified, open, standard-based network which was larger than that in the United States.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In February 1987 Europe produced the first agreed GSM Technical Specification.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Ministers from the EU Big Four (France, West Germany, United Kingdom and Italy) cemented their political support for GSM with the Bonn Declaration on Global Information Networks in May and the GSM MoU was tabled for signature in September.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The MoU drew in mobile operators from across Europe to pledge to invest in new GSM networks to an ambitious common date.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In this short 38-week period the whole of Europe (countries and industries) had been brought behind GSM, as guided by four public officials: Armin Silberhorn (Germany), Stephen Temple (UK), Philippe Dupuis (France), and Renzo Failli (Italy).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 1989 the Groupe Spécial Mobile committee was transferred from CEPT to the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The IEEE/RSE awarded to Thomas Haug and Philippe Dupuis the 2018 James Clerk Maxwell medal for their "leadership in the development of the first international mobile communications standard with subsequent evolution into worldwide smartphone data communication".
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The GSM (2G) has evolved into 3G, 4G and 5G.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In parallel France and Germany signed a joint development agreement in 1984 and were joined by Italy and the UK in 1986.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 1986, the European Commission proposed reserving the 900 MHz spectrum band for GSM.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] It was long believed that the former Finnish prime minister Harri Holkeri made the world's first GSM call on 1 July 1991, calling Kaarina Suonio (deputy mayor of the city of Tampere) using a network built by Nokia and Siemens and operated by Radiolinja.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 2021 a former Nokia engineer Pekka Lonka revealed to *Helsingin Sanomat* making a test call just a couple of hours earlier.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] "World's first GSM call was actually made by me.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] I called Marjo Jousinen, in Salo.", Lonka informed.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The following year saw the sending of the first short messaging service (SMS or "text message") message, and Vodafone UK and Telecom Finland signed the first international roaming agreement.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Work began in 1991 to expand the GSM standard to the 1800 MHz frequency band and the first 1800 MHz network (Mercury One2One) became operational in the UK by 1993, called the DCS 1800.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Also that year, Telstra became the first network operator to deploy a GSM network outside Europe and the first practical hand-held GSM mobile phone became available.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 1995 fax, data and SMS messaging services were launched commercially, the first 1900 MHz GSM network became operational in the United States and GSM subscribers worldwide exceeded 10 million.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In the same year, the GSM Association formed.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Pre-paid GSM SIM cards were launched in 1996 and worldwide GSM subscribers passed 100 million in 1998.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 2000 the first commercial General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) services were launched and the first GPRS-compatible handsets became available for sale.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 2001, the first UMTS (W-CDMA) network was launched, a 3G technology that is not part of GSM.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Worldwide GSM subscribers exceeded 500 million.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 2002, the first Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS) was introduced and the first GSM network in the 800 MHz frequency band became operational.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Enhanced Data rates for GSM Evolution (EDGE) services first became operational in a network in 2003, and the number of worldwide GSM subscribers exceeded 1 billion in 2004.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] By 2005 GSM networks accounted for more than 75% of the worldwide cellular network market, serving 1.5 billion subscribers.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In 2005, the first network capable to utilize High Speed Downlink Packet Access (HSDPA) also became operational.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The complementary High Speed Uplink Packet Access (HSUPA) technology's first network was launched in 2007.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The amalgamation of HSDPA and HSUPA is known as High Speed Packet Access (HSPA).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Even though HSPA, with its uplink and downlink versions, is 3G technology and not GSM, in 2008, worldwide GSM subscribers exceeded three billion.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The GSM Association estimated in 2011 that technologies defined in the GSM standard served 80% of the mobile market, encompassing more than 5 billion people across more than 212 countries and territories, making GSM the most ubiquitous of the many standards for cellular networks.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM is a second-generation (2G) standard employing time-division multiple-access (TDMA) spectrum-sharing, issued by the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The GSM standard does not include the 3G Universal Mobile Telecommunications System (UMTS), code-division multiple access (CDMA) technology, nor the 4G LTE orthogonal frequency-division multiple access (OFDMA) technology standards issued by the 3GPP.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM, for the first time, set a common standard for Europe for wireless networks.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] It was also adopted by many countries outside Europe.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] This allowed subscribers to use other GSM networks that have roaming agreements with each other.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The common standard reduced research and development costs, since hardware and software could be sold with only minor adaptations for the local market.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Telstra in Australia shut down its 2G GSM network on 1 December 2016, the first mobile network operator to decommission a GSM network.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The second mobile provider to shut down its GSM network (on 1 January 2017) was AT&T Mobility from the United States.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Optus in Australia completed the shut down of its 2G GSM network on 1 August 2017, part of the Optus GSM network covering Western Australia and the Northern Territory had earlier in the year been shut down in April 2017.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Singapore shut down 2G services entirely in April 2017.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM utilizes a cellular network, meaning that cell phones connect to it by searching for cells in the immediate vicinity.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The coverage area of each cell varies according to the implementation environment.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Macro cells can be regarded as cells where the base-station antenna is installed on a mast or a building above average rooftop level.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Micro cells are cells whose antenna height is under average rooftop level; they are typically deployed in urban areas.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Picocells are small cells whose coverage diameter is a few dozen meters; they are mainly used indoors.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Femtocells are cells designed for use in residential or small-business environments and connect to a telecommunications service provider's network via a broadband-internet connection.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Umbrella cells are used to cover shadowed regions of smaller cells and to fill in gaps in coverage between those cells.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Cell horizontal radius varies – depending on antenna height, antenna gain, and propagation conditions – from a couple of hundred meters to several tens of kilometers.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The longest distance the GSM specification supports in practical use is 35 kilometres (22 mi).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] There are also several implementations of the concept of an extended cell, where the cell radius could be double or even more, depending on the antenna system, the type of terrain, and the timing advance.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM supports indoor coverage – achievable by using an indoor picocell base station, or an indoor repeater with distributed indoor antennas fed through power splitters – to deliver the radio signals from an antenna outdoors to the separate indoor distributed antenna system.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Picocells are typically deployed when significant call capacity is needed indoors, as in shopping centers or airports.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] However, this is not a prerequisite, since indoor coverage is also provided by in-building penetration of radio signals from any nearby cell.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM networks operate in a number of different carrier frequency ranges (separated into GSM frequency ranges for 2G and UMTS frequency bands for 3G), with most 2G GSM networks operating in the 900 MHz or 1800 MHz bands.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Where these bands were already allocated, the 850 MHz and 1900 MHz bands were used instead (for example in Canada and the United States).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In rare cases the 400 and 450 MHz frequency bands are assigned in some countries because they were previously used for first-generation systems.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] For comparison, most 3G networks in Europe operate in the 2100 MHz frequency band.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] For more information on worldwide GSM frequency usage, see GSM frequency bands.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Regardless of the frequency selected by an operator, it is divided into timeslots for individual phones.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] This allows eight full-rate or sixteen half-rate speech channels per radio frequency.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] These eight radio timeslots (or burst periods) are grouped into a TDMA frame.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Half-rate channels use alternate frames in the same timeslot.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The channel data rate for all 8 channels is 270.833 kbit/s, and the frame duration is 4.615 ms.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] TDMA noise is interference that can be heard on speakers near a GSM phone using TDMA, audible as a buzzing sound.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The transmission power in the handset is limited to a maximum of 2 watts in GSM 850/900 and 1 watt in GSM 1800/1900.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM has used a variety of voice codecs to squeeze 3.1 kHz audio into between 7 and 13 kbit/s.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Originally, two codecs, named after the types of data channel they were allocated, were used, called Half Rate (6.5 kbit/s) and Full Rate (13 kbit/s).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] These used a system based on linear predictive coding (LPC).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] In addition to being efficient with bitrates, these codecs also made it easier to identify more important parts of the audio, allowing the air interface layer to prioritize and better protect these parts of the signal.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM was further enhanced in 1997 with the enhanced full rate (EFR) codec, a 12.2 kbit/s codec that uses a full-rate channel.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Finally, with the development of UMTS, EFR was refactored into a variable-rate codec called AMR-Narrowband, which is high quality and robust against interference when used on full-rate channels, or less robust but still relatively high quality when used in good radio conditions on half-rate channel.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] One of the key features of GSM is the Subscriber Identity Module, commonly known as a **SIM card**.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The SIM is a detachable smart card containing a user's subscription information and phone book.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] This allows users to retain their information after switching handsets.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Alternatively, users can change networks or network identities without switching handsets - simply by changing the SIM.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Sometimes mobile network operators restrict handsets that they sell for exclusive use in their own network.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] This is called SIM locking and is implemented by a software feature of the phone.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] A subscriber may usually contact the provider to remove the lock for a fee, utilize private services to remove the lock, or use software and websites to unlock the handset themselves.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] It is possible to hack past a phone locked by a network operator.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Brazil and Germany) all phones are sold unlocked due to the abundance of dual-SIM handsets and operators.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM was intended to be a secure wireless system.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] It has considered the user authentication using a pre-shared key and challenge–response, and over-the-air encryption.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] However, GSM is vulnerable to different types of attack, each of them aimed at a different part of the network.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Research findings indicate that GSM faces susceptibility to hacking by script kiddies, a term referring to inexperienced individuals utilizing readily available hardware and software.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The vulnerability arises from the accessibility of tools such as a DVB-T TV tuner, posing a threat to both mobile and network users.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Despite the term "script kiddies" implying a lack of sophisticated skills, the consequences of their attacks on GSM can be severe, impacting the functionality of cellular networks.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Given that GSM continues to be the main source of cellular technology in numerous countries, its susceptibility to potential threats from malicious attacks is one that needs to be addressed.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The development of UMTS introduced an optional Universal Subscriber Identity Module (USIM) that uses a longer authentication key to give greater security, as well as mutually authenticating the network and the user, whereas GSM only authenticates the user to the network (and not vice versa).
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The security model therefore offers confidentiality and authentication, but limited authorization capabilities, and no non-repudiation.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM uses several cryptographic algorithms for security.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The A5/1, A5/2, and A5/3 stream ciphers are used for ensuring over-the-air voice privacy.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] A5/1 was developed first and is a stronger algorithm used within Europe and the United States; A5/2 is weaker and used in other countries.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Serious weaknesses have been found in both algorithms: it is possible to break A5/2 in real-time with a ciphertext-only attack, and in January 2007, The Hacker's Choice started the A5/1 cracking project with plans to use FPGAs that allow A5/1 to be broken with a rainbow table attack.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The system supports multiple algorithms so operators may replace that cipher with a stronger one.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Since 2000, different efforts have been made in order to crack the A5 encryption algorithms.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Both A5/1 and A5/2 algorithms have been broken, and their cryptanalysis has been revealed in the literature.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] As an example, Karsten Nohl developed a number of rainbow tables (static values which reduce the time needed to carry out an attack) and have found new sources for known plaintext attacks.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] He said that it is possible to build "a full GSM interceptor ... from open-source components" but that they had not done so because of legal concerns.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Nohl claimed that he was able to intercept voice and text conversations by impersonating another user to listen to voicemail, make calls, or send text messages using a seven-year-old Motorola cellphone and decryption software available for free online.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GSM uses General Packet Radio Service (GPRS) for data transmissions like browsing the web.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The most commonly deployed GPRS ciphers were publicly broken in 2011.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The researchers revealed flaws in the commonly used GEA/1 and GEA/2 (standing for GPRS Encryption Algorithms 1 and 2) ciphers and published the open-source "gprsdecode" software for sniffing GPRS networks.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] They also noted that some carriers do not encrypt the data (i.e., using GEA/0) in order to detect the use of traffic or protocols they do not like (e.g., Skype), leaving customers unprotected.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] GEA/3 seems to remain relatively hard to break and is said to be in use on some more modern networks.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] If used with USIM to prevent connections to fake base stations and downgrade attacks, users will be protected in the medium term, though migration to 128-bit GEA/4 is still recommended.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The first public cryptanalysis of GEA/1 and GEA/2 (also written GEA-1 and GEA-2) was done in 2021.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] It concluded that although using a 64-bit key, the GEA-1 algorithm actually provides only 40 bits of security, due to a relationship between two parts of the algorithm.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The researchers found that this relationship was very unlikely to have happened if it was not intentional.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] This may have been done in order to satisfy European controls on export of cryptographic programs.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The GSM systems and services are described in a set of standards governed by ETSI, where a full list is maintained.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Several open-source software projects exist that provide certain GSM features, such as a base transceiver station by OpenBTS and the Osmocom stack providing various parts.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Patents remain a problem for any open-source GSM implementation, because it is not possible for GNU or any other free software distributor to guarantee immunity from all lawsuits by the patent holders against the users.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] Furthermore, new features are being added to the standard all the time which means they have patent protection for a number of years.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The original GSM implementations from 1991 may now be entirely free of patent encumbrances, however patent freedom is not certain due to the United States' "first to invent" system that was in place until 2012.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] The "first to invent" system, coupled with "patent term adjustment" can extend the life of a U.S. patent far beyond 20 years from its priority date.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] It is unclear at this time whether OpenBTS will be able to implement features of that initial specification without limit.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] As patents subsequently expire, however, those features can be added into the open-source version.
[src:sms-gateways/gsm] As of 2011, there have been no lawsuits against users of OpenBTS over GSM use.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Media companies have utilized MMS on a commercial basis as a method of delivering news and entertainment content, and retailers have deployed it as a tool for delivering scannable coupon codes, product images, videos, and other information.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] On (mainly) older devices, messages that start off with text, as SMS, are converted to and sent as an MMS when an emoji is added.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] The commercial introduction of MMS started in March 2002, although picture messaging had already been established in Japan.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] It was built using the technology of SMS as a captive technology which enabled service providers to "collect a fee every time anyone snaps a photo." MMS was designed to be able to work on the then-new GPRS and 3G networks and could be implemented through either a WAP-based or IP-based gateway.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] The 3GPP and WAP Forum groups fostered the development of the MMS standard, which was then continued by the Open Mobile Alliance (OMA).
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] MMS messages are delivered in a different way from SMS.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] The first step is for the sending device to encode the multimedia content in a fashion similar to sending a MIME message (MIME content formats are defined in the MMS Message Encapsulation specification).
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] The message is then forwarded to the carrier's MMS store and forward server, known as the **MMSC** (Multimedia Messaging Service Centre).
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] If the receiver is on a carrier different from the sender, then the MMSC acts as a relay, and forwards the message to the MMSC of the recipient's carrier using the Internet.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Once the recipient's MMSC has received a message, it first determines whether the receiver's handset is "MMS capable" or not.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] If it supports the standards for receiving MMS, the content is extracted and sent to a temporary storage server with an HTTP front-end.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] An SMS "control message" containing the URL of the content is then sent to the recipient's handset to trigger the receiver's WAP browser to open and receive the content from the embedded URL.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Several other messages are exchanged to indicate the status of the delivery attempt.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Before delivering content, some MMSCs also include a conversion service that will attempt to modify the multimedia content into a format suitable for the receiver.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] If the receiver's handset is not MMS capable, the message is usually delivered to a web-based service from where the content can be viewed from a normal web browser.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] The URL for the content is usually sent to the receiver's phone in a normal text message.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] This behavior is usually known as a "legacy experience" since content can still be received by the user.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] The method for determining whether a handset is MMS capable is not specified by the standards.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] A database is usually maintained by the operator, and in it each mobile phone number is marked as being associated with a legacy handset or not.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] This method is unreliable, however, because customers can independently change their handsets, and many of these databases are not updated dynamically.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] MMS does not utilize operator-maintained "data" plans to distribute multimedia content; they are used only if the user clicks links inside the message.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] E-mail and web-based gateways to the MMS system are common.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] On the reception side, the content servers can typically receive service requests both from WAP and normal HTTP browsers, so delivery via the web is simple.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] For sending from external sources to handsets, most carriers allow a MIME encoded message to be sent to the receiver's phone number using a special e-mail address combining the recipient's public phone number and a special domain name, which is typically carrier-specific.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Although the standard does not specify a maximum size for a message, 300 kB and 600 kB are the recommended sizes used by networks for compatibility with MMS 1.2 and MMS 1.3 devices respectively.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] The limit for the first generation of MMS was 50 kB.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Verizon launched its MMS service in July 2003.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Between 2010 and 2013, MMS traffic in the U.S. increased by 70% from 57 billion to 96 billion messages sent.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] This is due in part to the wide adoption of smartphones.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] However take-up of MMS never matched the widespread popularity of SMS text messaging.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] Due to lower cost and improved functionality provided by modern internet-based instant messengers such as WhatsApp, Telegram, and Signal, MMS usage has declined, and it has been discontinued by several telcos since the early 2020s.
[src:sms-gateways/multimedia-messaging-service] RCS is intended to be the successor technology for MMS and SMS.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] A **Short Message Service Center** (**SMSC**) is a network element in the mobile telephone network.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] Its purpose is to store, forward, convert and deliver Short Message Service (SMS) messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] When a user *sends* a text message (SMS message) to another user, the message gets stored in the SMSC (Short Message Service Center), which delivers it to the destination user when they are available.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] An SMS center (SMSC) is responsible for handling the SMS operations of a wireless network.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] The SMS center then forwards the SMS message towards the destination.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] The main duty of an SMSC is to route SMS messages and regulate the process.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] If the recipient is unavailable (for example, when the mobile phone is switched off), the SMSC will store the SMS CAR message.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] It will forward the SMS message when the recipient is available and the message's expiry period is not exceeded.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] SMSCs can be used to interface with other applications, for example a spreadsheet can interface with the SMSC allowing messages to be sent SMS from an Excel spreadsheet, or to send an SMS from Excel.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] Inbound messages to a long number or short code can also be passed through the SMSC allowing m2m communications or Telematics.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] An SMS message is stored temporarily in the SMS center if the recipient mobile phone is unavailable.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] It is possible on most mobile handsets to specify an expiry period after which the SMS message will be deleted from the SMS center.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] Once deleted, the SMS message will no longer be available for dispatch to the recipient mobile phone (even if it comes on line).
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] The validity period should be regarded by the handset user as a request, as the SMSC itself can be configured to ignore or otherwise handle message delivery schedules.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] The SMS sender needs to set a flag in the SMS message to notify the SMS center that they want the status report about the delivery of this SMS message.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service-center] This is usually done by changing a setting on the mobile handset.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Developed as part of the GSM standards, and based on the SS7 signalling protocol, SMS rolled out on digital cellular networks starting in 1993 and was originally intended for customers to receive alerts from their carrier/operator.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The service allows users to send and receive text messages of up to 160 characters, originally to and from GSM phones and later also CDMA and Digital AMPS; it has since been defined and supported on newer networks, including present-day 5G ones.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Using SMS gateways, messages can be transmitted over the Internet through an SMSC, allowing communication to computers, fixed landlines, and satellite.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] MMS was later introduced as an upgrade to SMS with "picture messaging" capabilities.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In addition to recreational texting between people, SMS is also used for mobile marketing (a type of direct marketing), two-factor authentication logging-in, televoting, mobile banking (see SMS banking), and for other commercial content.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The SMS standard has been hugely popular worldwide as a method of text communication: by the end of 2010, it was the most widely used data application with an estimated 3.5 billion active users, or about 80% of all mobile phone subscribers.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] More recently, SMS has become increasingly challenged by newer proprietary instant messaging services; Rich Communication Services (RCS) has been designated as the potential open standard successor to SMS.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS technology originated from radio telegraphy in radio memo pagers that used standardized phone protocols.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] These were defined in 1986 as part of the Global System for Mobile Communications (GSM) series of standards.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The first SMS message was sent on 3 December 1992, when Neil Papworth, a test engineer for Sema Group, sent "Merry Christmas" to the Orbitel 901 phone of colleague Richard Jarvis.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Adding text messaging functionality to mobile devices began in the early 1980s.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The SMS concept was developed in the Franco-German GSM cooperation in 1984 by Friedhelm Hillebrand and Bernard Ghillebaert.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The GSM is optimized for telephony, since this was identified as its main application.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The key idea for SMS was to use this telephone-optimized system, and to transport messages on the signalling paths needed to control the telephone traffic during periods when no signalling traffic existed.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In this way, unused resources in the system could be used to transport messages at minimal cost.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] However, it was necessary to limit the length of the messages to 128 bytes (later improved to 160 seven-bit characters) so that the messages could fit into the existing signalling formats.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Based on his personal observations and on analysis of the typical lengths of postcard and Telex messages, Hillebrand argued that 160 characters was sufficient for most brief communications.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS could be implemented in every mobile station by updating its software.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Hence, a large base of SMS-capable terminals and networks existed when people began to use SMS.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] A new network element required was a specialized short message service centre, and enhancements were required to the radio capacity and network transport infrastructure to accommodate growing SMS traffic.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The technical development of SMS was a multinational collaboration supporting the framework of standards bodies.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Through these organizations the technology was made freely available to the whole world.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The first proposal which initiated the development of SMS was made by a contribution of Germany and France in the GSM group meeting in February 1985 in Oslo.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] This proposal was further elaborated in GSM subgroup WP1 Services (Chairman Martine Alvernhe, France Telecom) based on a contribution from Germany.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] There were also initial discussions in the subgroup WP3 network aspects chaired by Jan Audestad (Telenor).
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The result was approved by the main GSM group in a June 1985 document which was distributed to industry.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The input documents on SMS had been prepared by Friedhelm Hillebrand of Deutsche Telekom, with contributions from Bernard Ghillebaert of France Télécom.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The definition that Friedhelm Hillebrand and Bernard Ghillebaert brought into GSM called for the provision of a message transmission service of alphanumeric messages to mobile users "with acknowledgement capabilities".
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The last three words transformed SMS into something much more useful than the electronic paging services used at the time that some in GSM might have had in mind.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS was considered in the main GSM group as a possible service for the new digital cellular system.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In GSM document "*Services and Facilities to be provided in the GSM System,*" both mobile-originated and mobile-terminated short messages appear on the table of GSM teleservices.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Short message mobile-originated (SMS-MO)/ Point-to-Point: the ability of a network to transmit a Short Message sent by a mobile phone.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The message can be sent to a phone or to a software application.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] WP4 created a Drafting Group Message Handling (DGMH), which was responsible for the specification of SMS.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Finn Trosby of Telenor chaired the draft group through its first three years, in which the design of SMS was established.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] DGMH had five to eight participants, and Finn Trosby mentions as major contributors Kevin Holley, Eija Altonen, Didier Luizard and Alan Cox.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The first action plan mentions for the first time the Technical Specification 03.40 "Technical Realisation of the Short Message Service".
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The first and very rudimentary draft of the technical specification was completed in November 1987.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] However, drafts useful for the manufacturers followed at a later stage in the period.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] A comprehensive description of the work in this period is given in.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The first SMS message was sent over the Vodafone GSM network in the United Kingdom on 3 December 1992, from Neil Papworth of Sema Group (now Mavenir Systems) using a personal computer to Richard Jarvis of Vodafone using an Orbitel 901 handset.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The first commercial deployment of a short message service center (SMSC) was by Aldiscon part of Logica (now part of CGI) with Telia (now TeliaSonera) in Sweden in 1993, followed by Fleet Call (now Nextel) in the US, Telenor in Norway and BT Cellnet (now O2 UK).
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The first commercially sold SMS service was offered to consumers, as a person-to-person text messaging service by Radiolinja (now part of Elisa) in Finland in 1993.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Most early GSM mobile phone handsets did not support the ability to send SMS text messages, and Nokia was the only handset manufacturer whose total GSM phone line in 1993 supported user-sending of SMS text messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] According to Matti Makkonen, an engineer at Nokia at the time, the Nokia 2010, which was released in January 1994, was the first mobile phone to support composing SMSes easily.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Initial growth was slow, with customers in 1995 sending on average only 0.4 messages per GSM customer per month.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Initially, networks in the UK only allowed customers to send messages to other users on the same network, limiting the usefulness of the service.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Over time, this issue was eliminated by switch billing instead of billing at the SMSC and by new features within SMSCs to allow blocking of foreign mobile users sending messages through it.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] By the end of 2000, the average number of messages reached 35 per user per month, and on Christmas Day 2006, over 205 million messages were sent in the UK alone.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS had become a social phenomenon in Finland among teens and youngsters by 1999.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS traffic across Europe reached 4 billion messages as of January 2000.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS became extremely popular in the Philippines by 2001 and the country was dubbed the "texting capital of the world", partly helped by large numbers of free text messages offered by the mobile operators in monthly subscriptions.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS adoption was limited to parts of Europe and Asia during these earlier years, with U.S. adoption being low partly due to incompatible networks and cheap voice calls relative to other countries.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS has become a large commercial industry, earning $114.6 billion globally in 2010.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In the year 2002, 366 billion SMS text messages were sent globally, a number that rose to 6.1 trillion in 2010.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In 2015, the actual cost of sending an SMS in Australia was found to be $0.00016 per SMS.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The global SMS messaging business was estimated to be worth over US$240 billion in 2013, accounting for almost half of all revenue generated by mobile messaging.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The popularity of SMS also led to the spontaneous creation of the so-called 'SMS language' phenomenon, where words are shortened in order to deal with the 160 character limit of SMS messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Usage of SMS for mobile data services became increasingly prominent in the early 2000s due to its ubiquity, reliability, and cold reception of the newer WAP standard.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In the early and mid 2000s, Multimedia Messaging Service (MMS) was developed as an improved version of SMS that supports sending of pictures and video.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS has been increasingly challenged by Internet Protocol-based messaging services with additional features for modern mobile devices, such as Facebook Messenger, WhatsApp, Telegram, or WeChat.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] These services run independently from mobile network operators and typically don't provide cross-platform messaging capabilities like SMS or email does.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] For example, between 2010 and 2022, SMS telecom revenue in India dropped 94 percent, while "revenue share per user from data usage...grew over 10 times.", although in some regions such as North America SMS continues to be used by over 80 percent of the population as of 2023.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In order to create a modern successor to SMS that isn't run by a single company and is fully interoperable between devices, industry figures have created the RCS 'Universal Profile' initiative.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] It was supported by Apple when iOS 18 came out in 2024, which will mean that virtually all new mobile phones (iOS and Android platforms) will have RCS texting capabilities, though this may also depend on if the network operator supports it.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS may be used to provide premium rate services to subscribers of a network.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Today, they are also used to pay smaller payments online—for example, for file-sharing services, in mobile application stores, or VIP section entrance.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Outside the online world, one can buy a bus ticket or beverages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Additionally, an intermediary service can facilitate a text-to-voice conversion to be sent to landlines.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In 2014, Caktus Group developed the world's first SMS-based voter registration system in Libya.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] As of February 2015 more than 1.5 million people have registered using that system, providing Libyan voters with unprecedented access to the democratic process.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] A Flash SMS is a type of SMS that appears directly on the main screen without user interaction and is not automatically stored in the inbox.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] It can be useful in emergencies, such as a fire alarm or cases of confidentiality, as in delivering one-time passwords.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In 2010, almost half a million silent SMS messages were sent by the German federal police, customs and the federal domestic intelligence service Verfassungsschutz.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] These silent messages, also known as silent TMS, stealth SMS, stealth ping or Short Message Type 0, are used to locate a person and thus to create a complete movement profile.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] They do not show up on a display, nor trigger any acoustical signal when received.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Their primary purpose was to deliver special services of the network operator to any cell phone.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In March 2001, Dutch police in Amsterdam attempted to fight increasing cell phone theft by sending an SMS every three minutes to a phone that has been reported stolen, with the message "This handset was nicked, buying or selling is a crime.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The *Short Message Service—Point to Point (SMS-PP)*—was originally defined in GSM recommendation 03.40, which is now maintained in 3GPP as TS 23.040.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] GSM 03.41 (now 3GPP TS 23.041) defines the *Short Message Service—Cell Broadcast (SMS-CB)*, which allows messages (advertising, public information, etc.) to be broadcast to all mobile users in a specified geographical area.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Cell broadcast is the technology behind Wireless Emergency Alerts in the US which is used for public safety messages and AMBER alerts, and similar public safety messages in other countries.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] These messages are similar to SMS messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Messages are sent to a short message service center (SMSC), which provides a "store and forward" mechanism.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] It attempts to send messages to the SMSC's recipients.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] If a recipient is not reachable, the SMSC queues the message for later retry.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Some SMSCs also provide a "forward and forget" option where transmission is tried only once.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Both mobile terminated (MT, for messages sent *to* a mobile handset) and mobile originating (MO, for those sent *from* the mobile handset) operations are supported.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Message delivery is "best effort", so there are no guarantees that a message will actually be delivered to its recipient, but delay or complete loss of a message is uncommon, typically affecting less than 5 percent of messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Some providers allow users to request delivery reports, either via the SMS settings of most modern phones, or by prefixing each message with *0#.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Transmission of short messages between the SMSC and the handset is done whenever using the Mobile Application Part (MAP) of the SS7 protocol.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Messages are sent with the MAP MO- and MT-ForwardSM operations, whose payload length is limited by the constraints of the signaling protocol to precisely 140 bytes (140 bytes × 8 bits / byte = 1120 bits).
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Short messages can be encoded using a variety of alphabets: the default GSM 7-bit alphabet, the 8-bit data alphabet, and the 16-bit UCS-2 or UTF-16 alphabets.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Depending on which alphabet the subscriber has configured in the handset, this leads to the maximum individual short message sizes of 160 7-bit characters, 140 8-bit characters, or 70 16-bit characters.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] GSM 7-bit alphabet support is mandatory for GSM handsets and network elements.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Larger content (concatenated SMS, multipart or segmented SMS, or "long SMS") can be sent using multiple messages, in which case each message will start with a User Data Header (UDH) containing segmentation information.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Since UDH is part of the payload, the number of available characters per segment is lower: 153 for 7-bit encoding, 134 for 8-bit encoding and 67 for 16-bit encoding.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The receiving handset is then responsible for reassembling the message and presenting it to the user as one long message.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] While the standard theoretically permits up to 255 segments, 10 segments is the practical maximum with some carriers, and long messages are often billed as equivalent to multiple SMS messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In some cases 127 segments are supported.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] On some carriers non-subscribers can send messages to a subscriber's phone using an Email-to-SMS gateway.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Additionally, many carriers, including AT&T Mobility, T-Mobile USA, Sprint, and Verizon Wireless, offer the ability to do this through their respective websites.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] For example, an AT&T subscriber whose phone number was 555-555-5555 would receive emails addressed to 5555555555@txt.att.net as text messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Subscribers can easily reply to these SMS messages, and the SMS reply is sent back to the original email address.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Sending email to SMS is free for the sender, but the recipient is subject to the standard delivery charges.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Only the first 160 characters of an email message can be delivered to a phone, and only 160 characters can be sent from a phone.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] However, longer messages may be broken up into multiple texts, depending upon the telephone service provider.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Text-enabled fixed-line handsets are required to receive messages in text format.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] However, messages can be delivered to non enabled phones using text-to-speech conversion.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Short messages can send binary content such as ringtones or logos, as well as Over-the-air programming (OTA) or configuration data.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Such uses are a vendor-specific extension of the GSM specification and there are multiple competing standards, although Nokia's Smart Messaging is common.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] GPRS is offered by smaller telco players as a route of sending SMS text to reduce the cost of SMS texting internationally.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The Mobile Application Part (MAP) of the SS7 protocol included support for the transport of Short Messages through the Core Network from its inception.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] MAP Phase 2 expanded support for SMS by introducing a separate operation code for Mobile Terminated Short Message transport.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Many mobile and satellite transceiver units support the sending and receiving of SMS using an extended version of the Hayes command set.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The extensions were standardised as part of the GSM Standards and extended as part of the 3GPP standards process.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The connection between the terminal equipment and the transceiver can be realized with a serial cable (e.g., USB), a Bluetooth link, an infrared link, etc.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Common AT commands include AT+CMGS (send message), AT+CMSS (send message from storage), AT+CMGL (list messages) and AT+CMGR (read message).
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] However, not all modern devices support receiving of messages if the message storage (for instance the device's internal memory) is not accessible using AT commands.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] An alternative to inbound SMS is based on long numbers (international number format, such as "+44 762 480 5000"), which can be used in place of short codes for SMS reception in several applications, such as TV voting, product promotions and campaigns.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Long numbers work internationally, allow businesses to use their own numbers, rather than short codes, which are usually shared across many brands.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Additionally, long numbers are nonpremium inbound numbers.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Threaded SMS is a visual styling orientation of SMS message history that arranges messages to and from a contact in chronological order on a single screen.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Visually, this style of representation provides a back-and-forth chat-like history for each individual contact.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Hierarchical-threading at the conversation-level (as typical in blogs and online messaging boards) is not widely supported by SMS messaging clients.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Session-tracking is used to extend the functionality of many Instant Messenger (IM) applications such that they are able to communicate over two-way dialogues with the much larger SMS user-base.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] While SMS reached its popularity as a person-to-person messaging, another type of SMS became popular by 2017: application-to-person (A2P) messaging.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] A2P is a type of SMS sent from a subscriber to an application or sent from an application to a subscriber.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] It is commonly used by businesses, such as banks, e-gaming, logistic companies, e-commerce, to send SMS messages from their systems to their customers.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In the US, carriers have traditionally preferred that A2P messages be sent using a short code rather than a standard long code.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In 2021, US carriers introduced a new service called A2P 10DLC, supporting the used of 10-digit long codes for A2P messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In the United Kingdom A2P messages can be sent with a dynamic 11 character sender ID; however, short codes are used for OPTOUT commands.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] While early Iridium handsets only support incoming SMS, later models can also send messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The price per message varies for different networks.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Unlike some mobile phone networks, there is no extra charge for sending international SMS or to send one to a different satellite phone network.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS can sometimes be sent from areas where the signal is too poor to make a voice call.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Satellite phone networks usually have web-based or email-based SMS portals where one can send free SMS to phones on that particular network.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Unlike dedicated texting systems like the Simple Network Paging Protocol and Motorola's ReFLEX protocol, SMS message delivery is not guaranteed, and many implementations provide no mechanism through which a sender can determine whether an SMS message has been delivered in a timely manner.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS messages are generally treated as lower-priority traffic than voice, and various studies have shown that around 1% to 5% of messages are lost entirely, even during normal operation conditions, and others may not be delivered until long after their relevance has passed.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The use of SMS as an emergency notification service in particular has been questioned.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The Global Service for Mobile communications (GSM), with the greatest worldwide number of users, succumbs to several security vulnerabilities.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In the GSM, only the airway traffic between the Mobile Station (MS) and the Base Transceiver Station (BTS) is optionally encrypted with a weak and broken stream cipher (A5/1 or A5/2).
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The authentication is unilateral and also vulnerable.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] There are also many other security vulnerabilities and shortcomings.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Such vulnerabilities are inherent to SMS as one of the superior and well-tried services with a global availability in the GSM networks.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] SMS messaging has some extra security vulnerabilities due to its store-and-forward feature, and the problem of fake SMS that can be conducted via the Internet.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] When a user is roaming, SMS content passes through different networks, perhaps including the Internet, and is exposed to various vulnerabilities and attacks.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Another concern arises when an adversary gets access to a phone and reads the previous unprotected messages.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In October 2005, researchers from the Pennsylvania State University published an analysis of vulnerabilities in SMS-capable cellular networks.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The researchers speculated that attackers might exploit the open functionality of these networks to disrupt them or cause them to fail, possibly on a nationwide scale.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The GSM industry has identified a number of potential fraud attacks on mobile operators that can be delivered via abuse of SMS messaging services.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] One threat is SMS spoofing, which occurs when a fraudster manipulates address information in order to impersonate a user that has roamed onto a foreign network and is submitting messages to the home network.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] Frequently, these messages are addressed to destinations outside the home network—with the home SMSC essentially being "hijacked" to send messages into other networks.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] The only sure way of detecting and blocking spoofed messages is to screen incoming mobile-originated messages to verify that the sender is a valid subscriber and that the message is coming from a valid and correct location.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] This can be implemented by adding an intelligent routing function to the network that can query originating subscriber details from the home location register (HLR) before the message is submitted for delivery.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] This kind of intelligent routing function is beyond the capabilities of legacy messaging infrastructure.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] In an effort to limit telemarketers who had taken to bombarding users with hordes of unsolicited messages, India introduced new regulations in September 2011, including a cap of 3,000 SMS messages per subscriber per month, or an average of 100 per subscriber per day.
[src:sms-gateways/short-message-service] However, it was ruled unconstitutional by the Delhi high court, but there are some limitations.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The protocol was introduced in the Bell System in the United States by the name *Common Channel Interoffice Signaling* in the 1970s for signaling between No.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The SS7 protocol is defined for international use by the Q.700-series recommendations of 1988 by the ITU-T.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Of the many national variants of the SS7 protocols, most are based on variants standardized by the American National Standards Institute (ANSI) and the European Telecommunications Standards Institute (ETSI).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] National variants with striking characteristics are the Chinese and Japanese Telecommunication Technology Committee (TTC) national variants.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SS7 has been shown to have several security vulnerabilities, allowing location tracking of callers, interception of voice data, intercept two-factor authentication keys, and possibly the delivery of spyware to phones.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) has defined the SIGTRAN protocol suite that implements levels 2, 3, and 4 protocols compatible with SS7.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Sometimes also called *Pseudo SS7*, it is layered on the Stream Control Transmission Protocol (SCTP) transport mechanism for use on Internet Protocol networks, such as the Internet.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In North America, SS7 is also often referred to as *Common Channel Signaling System 7* (CCSS7) (or CCS7).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In the United Kingdom, it is called *C7* (CCITT number 7), *number 7* and *Common Channel Interoffice Signaling 7* (CCIS7).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In Germany, it is often called *Zentraler Zeichengabekanal Nummer 7* (ZZK-7).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] 5 and earlier systems use in-band signaling, in which the call-setup information is sent by generating special multi-frequency tones transmitted on the telephone line audio channels, also known as *bearer channels*.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Since the bearer channels are directly accessible by users, they can be exploited with devices such as the blue box, which can replicate the tones used by the network for call control and routing.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] As a remedy, SS6 and SS7 implements out-of-band signaling, carried in a separate signaling channel, thus keeping the call control and speech paths separate.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SS6 and SS7 are referred to as common-channel signaling (CCS) protocols, or *Common Channel Interoffice Signaling* (CCIS) systems.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Another element of in-band signaling addressed by SS7 is network efficiency.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] With in-band signaling, the voice channel is used during call setup which makes it unavailable for actual traffic.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] For long-distance calls, the talk path may traverse several nodes which reduces usable node capacity.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] With SS7, the connection is not established between the end points until all nodes on the path confirm availability.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] If the far end is busy, the caller gets a busy signal without consuming a voice channel.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Since 1975, CCS protocols have been developed by major telephone companies and the International Telecommunication Union Telecommunication Standardization Sector (ITU-T); in 1977 the ITU-T defined the first international CCS protocol as Signaling System No.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In its 1980 Yellow Book Q.7XX-series recommendations ITU-T defined the Signaling System No.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SS7 replaced SS6 with its restricted 28-bit signal unit that was both limited in function and not amenable to digital systems.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] 5 (SS5), while R1 and R2 variants are still used in numerous countries.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) defined SIGTRAN protocols which translate the common channel signaling paradigm to the IP Message Transfer Part (MTP) level 2 (M2UA and M2PA), Message Transfer Part (MTP) level 3 (M3UA) and Signaling Connection Control Part (SCCP) (SUA).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] While running on a transport based upon IP, the SIGTRAN protocols are not an SS7 variant, but simply transport existing national and international variants of SS7.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Signaling in telephony is the exchange of control information associated with the setup and release of a telephone call on a telecommunications circuit.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Examples of control information are the digits dialed by the caller and the caller's billing number.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] When signaling is performed on the same circuit as the conversation of the call, it is termed channel-associated signaling (CAS).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This is the case for analogue trunks, multi-frequency (MF) and R2 digital trunks, and DSS1/DASS PBX trunks.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In contrast, SS7 uses common channel signaling, in which the path and facility used by the signaling is separate and distinct from the signaling without first seizing a voice channel, leading to significant savings and performance increases in both signaling and channel usage.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Because of the mechanisms in use by signaling methods prior to SS7 (battery reversal, multi-frequency digit outpulsing, A- and B-bit signaling), these earlier methods cannot communicate much signaling information.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Usually only the dialed digits are signaled during call setup.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] For charged calls, dialed digits and charge number digits are outpulsed.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SS7, being a high-speed and high-performance packet-based communications protocol, can communicate significant amounts of information when setting up a call, during the call, and at the end of the call.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This permits rich call-related services to be developed.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Some of the first such services were call management related, call forwarding (busy and no answer), voice mail, call waiting, conference calling, calling name and number display, call screening, malicious caller identification, busy callback.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The earliest deployed upper-layer protocols in the SS7 suite were dedicated to the setup, maintenance, and release of telephone calls.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The Telephone User Part (TUP) was adopted in Europe and the Integrated Services Digital Network (ISDN) User Part (ISUP) adapted for public switched telephone network (PSTN) calls was adopted in North America.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] ISUP was later used in Europe when the European networks upgraded to the ISDN.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] As of 2020 North America has not accomplished full upgrade to the ISDN, and the predominant telephone service is still Plain Old Telephone Service.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Due to its richness and the need for an out-of-band channel for its operation, SS7 is mostly used for signaling between telephone switches and not for signaling between local exchanges and customer-premises equipment.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Because SS7 signaling does not require seizure of a channel for a conversation prior to the exchange of control information, non-facility associated signaling (NFAS) became possible.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] NFAS is signaling that is not directly associated with the path that a conversation will traverse and may concern other information located at a centralized database such as service subscription, feature activation, and service logic.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] It also permits the subscriber increased mobility due to the decoupling of service logic from the subscription switch.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Another ISUP characteristic SS7 with NFAS enables is the exchange of signaling information during the middle of a call.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SS7 also enables Non-Call-Associated Signaling, which is signaling not directly related to establishing a telephone call.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This includes the exchange of registration information used between a mobile telephone and a home location register database, which tracks the location of the mobile.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Other examples include Intelligent Network and local number portability databases.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Apart from signaling with these various degrees of association with call set-up and the facilities used to carry calls, SS7 is designed to operate in two modes: *associated mode* and *quasi-associated mode*.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] When operating in the *associated mode*, SS7 signaling progresses from switch to switch through the Public Switched Telephone Network following the same path as the associated facilities that carry the telephone call.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This mode is more economical for small networks.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The associated mode of signaling is not the predominant choice of modes in North America.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] When operating in the *quasi-associated mode*, SS7 signaling progresses from the originating switch to the terminating switch, following a path through a separate SS7 signaling network composed of signal transfer points.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This mode is more economical for large networks with lightly loaded signaling links.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The quasi-associated mode of signaling is the predominant choice of modes in North America.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SS7 separates signaling from the voice circuits.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] An SS7 network must be made up of SS7-capable equipment from end to end in order to provide its full functionality.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The network can be made up of several link types (A, B, C, D, E, and F) and three signaling nodes – Service Switching Points (SSPs), Signal Transfer Points (STPs), and Service Control Points (SCPs).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Each node is identified on the network by a number, a signaling point code.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Extended services are provided by a database interface at the SCP level using the SS7 network.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The links between nodes are full-duplex 56, 64, 1,536, or 1,984 kbit/s graded communications channels.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In Europe they are usually one (64 kbit/s) or all (1,984 kbit/s) timeslots (DS0s) within an E1 facility; in North America one (56 or 64 kbit/s) or all (1,536 kbit/s) timeslots (DS0As or DS0s) within a T1 facility.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] One or more signaling links can be connected to the same two endpoints that together form a signaling link set.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Signaling links are added to link sets to increase the signaling capacity of the link set.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In Europe, SS7 links normally are directly connected between switching exchanges using F-links.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This direct connection is called *associated signaling*.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In North America, SS7 links are normally indirectly connected between switching exchanges using an intervening network of STPs (Signaling Transfer Points).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This indirect connection is called *quasi-associated signaling*, which reduces the number of SS7 links necessary to interconnect all switching exchanges and SCPs in an SS7 signaling network.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SS7 links at higher signaling capacity (1.536 and 1.984 Mbit/s, simply referred to as the 1.5 Mbit/s and 2.0 Mbit/s rates) are called high-speed links (HSL) in contrast to the low speed (56 and 64 kbit/s) links.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] High-speed links are specified in ITU-T Recommendation Q.703 for the 1.5 Mbit/s and 2.0 Mbit/s rates, and ANSI Standard T1.111.3 for the 1.536 Mbit/s rate.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] There are differences between the specifications for the 1.5 Mbit/s rate.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] High-speed links utilize the entire bandwidth of a T1 (1.536 Mbit/s) or E1 (1.984 Mbit/s) transmission facility for the transport of SS7 signaling messages.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SIGTRAN provides signaling using SCTP associations over the Internet Protocol.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The protocols for SIGTRAN are M2PA, M2UA, M3UA and SUA.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The SS7 protocol stack may be partially mapped to the OSI Model of a packetized digital protocol stack.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Currently there are no protocol components that provide OSI layers 4 through 6.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The Transaction Capabilities Application Part (TCAP) is the primary SCCP User in the Core Network, using SCCP in connectionless mode.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SCCP in connection oriented mode provides transport layer for air interface protocols such as BSSAP and RANAP.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] TCAP provides transaction capabilities to its Users (TC-Users), such as the Mobile Application Part, the Intelligent Network Application Part and the CAMEL Application Part.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The Message Transfer Part (MTP) covers a portion of the functions of the OSI network layer including: network interface, information transfer, message handling and routing to the higher levels.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Signaling Connection Control Part (SCCP) is at functional Level 4.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Together with MTP Level 3 it is called the Network Service Part (NSP).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] SCCP completes the functions of the OSI network layer: end-to-end addressing and routing, connectionless messages (UDTs), and management services for users of the Network Service Part (NSP).
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Telephone User Part (TUP) is a link-by-link signaling system used to connect calls.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] ISUP is the key user part, providing a circuit-based protocol to establish, maintain, and end the connections for calls.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Transaction Capabilities Application Part (TCAP) is used to create database queries and invoke advanced network functionality, or links to Intelligent Network Application Part (INAP) for intelligent networks, or Mobile Application Part (MAP) for mobile services.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In 2008, several SS7 vulnerabilities were published that permitted the tracking of mobile phone users.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In 2014, the media reported a protocol vulnerability of SS7 by which anyone can track the movements of mobile phone users from virtually anywhere in the world with a success rate of approximately 70%.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In addition, eavesdropping is possible by using the protocol to forward calls and also facilitate decryption by requesting that each caller's carrier release a temporary encryption key to unlock the communication after it has been recorded.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The software tool *SnoopSnitch* can warn when certain SS7 attacks occur against a phone, and detect IMSI-catchers that allow call interception and other activities.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In February 2016, 30% of the network of the largest mobile operator in Norway, Telenor, became unstable due to "unusual SS7 signaling from another European operator".
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The security vulnerabilities of SS7 have been highlighted in U.S. governmental bodies, for example when in April 2016 Congressman Ted Lieu called for an oversight committee investigation.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In May 2017, O2 Telefónica, a German mobile service provider, confirmed that the SS7 vulnerabilities had been exploited to bypass two-factor authentication to achieve unauthorized withdrawals from bank accounts.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The perpetrators installed malware on compromised computers, allowing them to collect online banking account credentials and telephone numbers.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] They set up redirects for the victims' telephone numbers to telephone lines controlled by them.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Confirmation calls and SMS text messages of two-factor authentication procedures were routed to telephone numbers controlled by the attackers.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] This enabled them to log into victims' online bank accounts and effect money transfers.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In March 2018, a method was published for the detection of the vulnerabilities, through the use of open-source monitoring software such as Wireshark and Snort.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] The nature of SS7 normally being used between consenting network operators on dedicated links means that any bad actor's traffic can be traced to its source.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] An investigation by *The Guardian* and the Bureau of Investigative Journalism revealed that the SS7 protocol was exploited in an attempt to locate Sheikha Latifa bint Mohammed Al Maktoum (II) on 3 March 2018, a day before her abduction.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In 2024, Kevin Briggs, an official at the Cybersecurity and Infrastructure Security Agency, reported to the FCC that hacks related to SS7 and Diameter had been used in "numerous attempts" to acquire location data, voice and text messages; to deliver spyware; and to influence voters in the US.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] In December 2024, U.S. senator Ron Wyden released information showing that the United States Department of Homeland Security believes China, Russia, Iran, and Israel are the primary countries exploiting SS7 for espionage.
[src:sms-gateways/signalling-system-no-7] Similar reports were made by POST Luxembourg.
